Notes: Named after Aaron, the older brother of Moses in the Hebrew Bible.[8]
Lake Named for Addie Hoag, the daughter of settler Charles Hoag.[8]
Named for Ole Alberts, a pioneer farmer who settled there.[8]: 182
Named for John B. Altermatt, a Swiss settler.[8]: 72

[9] This 54 acre lake has a maximum depth of 47 feet (14 m). There anglers can catch from 13 varieties of fish including Black Bullhead, Bluegill, Brown Bullhead, Largemouth Bass, Northern Pike, Rock Bass, Yellow Bullhead, Yellow Perch and Pumpkinseed.[10]
Asserted to be named for a bachelor.[8]
Also in Manitoba and Ontario, Canada
This lake is 96 acres with a maximum depth of 15 feet. There anglers can expect to catch Largemouth Bass, Rock Bass, Pumpkinseed Sunfish, Hybrid Sunfish, Bluegill, and Northern Pike.
Also partially in Ontario, Canada, and Wisconsin and Michigan

This 18 acre lake is named for being split into 3 separate but connected bodies of water by County Road 180 and 150th St. The lake has a maximum depth of about 12 Feet. There anglers can expect to catch many Brown Bullhead and a very rare Green Sunfish.
